    163 Chapter 10: Engine Gasket FEM Solution s Main Index 4095 3 -1. Alternatively, the BOLT option can be used. Although the kinematic constraints involved are the same, the BOLT option has the following advantages: the input format is more concise; the option is easier to use in a contact analysis. When the MPC entries are used, the user defined MPC’s may easily be conflicting with MPC’s introduced by the contact algorithm, thus causing the contact constraints to be skipped. On the other hand, when the elements at both sides of the cross section are included in the same contact body, then the BOLT option causes the contact algorithm to treat this cross section in a special way, Consequently, grid points at the boundary of the cross section can touch another contact body, while grid points touching the body with the cross section can slide along this body, even when the cross section has to be passed. Using the same control grids as mentioned above, the input of the BOLT entries is: BOLT 1 4083 TOP 3924 3930 3936 3942 3948 3954 3960 3966 3972 3978 3984 BOTTOM 4084 4085 4086 4087 4088 4089 4090 4091 4092 4093 4094 BOLT 2 4095 TOP 1918 1924 1930 1936 1942 1948 1954 1960 1966 1972 1978 BOTTOM 4096 4097 4098 4099 4100 4101 4102 4103 4104 4105 4106 The SPCDs defining the shortening of the bolts are: SPCD 1 4083 2 .175 SPCD 1 4095 2 .175 As discussed above, when using MPC’s or the BOLT functionality, the bolts were piece wise modeled by two parts, one upper and one lower part, obtained by a fictitious cut, in order to apply pre-tensioning on the bolts using MPC’s. Another alternative is to use the enhanced bolt modeling capability offered by BOLT1. The BOLT1 capability simulates the effect of bolt pre-tension and shortening by modifying the elements on one side of an arbitrary cross-section in the bolt without the need for splitting the bolt finite element mesh into top and bottom parts and duplicating the grid points on the bolt cross-section. This greatly simplifies the bolt modeling process. For the BOLT1 entry, the user has two options to input the data required for bolt modeling: the cross-section method and the simple method. Using the cross-section method, the user has more control in defining the bolt axial direction and cross-section selection. The user enters the vector defining the bolt axis, enters the list of grid points forming the bolt cross-section as well as the list of elements sharing cross-section grid points and lying on the opposite side of the normal vector. These are the elements that will be internally connected to the bolt control grid point. With the simple method of BOLT1 entry, modeling of bolts is further simplified by not requiring the user to enter the bolt axial direction or define the bolt cross-section nodes or select the layer of elements where the pre-tension loads will be applied. The user only needs to enter the list of elements forming the complete bolt and the program will automatically find the bolt normal direction and choose the cross-section nodes and elements. The code will find the centroid of the bolt, determine the bolt axial direction by examining the value of the bolt principal moment of inertia around the centroid then

    MSC Nastran Demonstration Problems FEM Solution s164 Main Index select the bolt cross-section by finding the lists of nodes and elements passing through the centroid and perpendicular to the axial direction. The engine gasket model has been modified to use the BOLT1 capability. A new model is created in which bolts are not split into top and bottom parts as shown in Figure 10-5. In the new model, the bolt control grid points, 4147 and 4148, of the two bolts each has an enforced displacement on an SPCD Bulk Data entry of 0.175 mm representing the bolt shortening preload. Figure 10-9 Stress distribution using BOLT1 and BOLT Modeling Tips Contact Body Definition Since the mesh of the engine block and the lower part of the bolts is a continuous mesh, the automated contact algorithm will not be able to find a unique boundary description at the interface of the engine block and the bolts. This is reflected by messages like: warning: node 1407 belongs to bodies 3 4. for the contact algorithm it will belong to body 3 only. Although, in the current example, this will not affect the results (there will be no contact detection between the engine block and the bolts), it is generally not recommended. Instead, one should either make sure that the lower part of the bolts are separated from the engine block or include only the upper part of the bolts in the contact body definition.

    MSC Nastran Demonstration Problems Introduction168 Main Index Introduction A model of a cylindrical pipe is subjected to crushing as rigid bodies above and below the pipe move inward towards each other. The model is created using nonlinear thick shell elements to model the pipe and rigid surfaces above and below the pipe. The problem attempts to quantify whether the movement of the external structures cause the plastic collapse of the pipe. Initial contact with the external structures is expected to cause elastic deformation of the steel pipe. Additional incremental movement potentially subjects the structure to stresses beyond the proportional limit of the material. The yield stress defines the onset of plastic strains that may initiate the collapse of the structure walls. This exercise illustrates several SOL 400 capabilities including large displacement analysis, contact analysis between rigid and deformable bodies, and large strain plasticity modeled with an elastic-perfectly plastic model.Applied loads Both rigid bodies are moving towards the pipe in y-direction by 2in using load controlled rigid body motion. Element type 4-node nonlinear thick shell element FE results Plot of y-displacement and Nonlinear plastic strain contours

    MSC Nastran Demonstration Problems Results174 Main Index Solution Procedure The nonlinear procedure used is defined through the following NLSTEP entry: NLSTEP 1 1. +

    •   GENERAL 500                                                     +       

    •   FIXED   50                                                      +       

    •   MECH    UPV                             PFNT

    where 50 indicates the total number of increments; PFNT represents Pure Full Newton-Raphson Technique wherein the stiffness is reformed at every iteration; KSTEP = 0 in conjunction with PFNT indicates that the program automatically determines if the stiffness needs to be reformed after the previous load increment is completed and the next load increment is commenced. 500 is the maximum number of allowed recycles for every increment and if this were to be exceeded, the load step would be cut-back and the increment repeated. UPV indicates that convergence will be checked on displacements (U) and residuals ( P) and V stands for vector component which will do a maximum component check.
